  "plan": "# Restaurant Booking Eval Implementation Plan\n\n## Scope and Shape\n\n- Build a small monorepo-style app with `backend/` for .NET 10 Minimal API and `frontend/` for a Vite React SPA.\n- Use in-memory persistence with seeded restaurants, tables, and bookings to keep the eval focused on behavior.\n- Organize backend by vertical slices: restaurant listing, available slots, create booking, existing bookings.\n- Keep domain rules in pure Functional Core files and HTTP/storage wiring in thin Imperative Shell files, using explicit `Result<T>`-style errors for expected failures.\n- Keep Clean Architecture lightweight: domain models/rules, in-memory store abstraction, endpoint slices, and tests.\n\n## Backend Vertical TDD Slices\n\n1. Bootstrap .NET 10 solution with a Web API project, xUnit test project, warnings-as-errors, nullable enabled, formatting config, OpenAPI enabled, CORS for the SPA, and deterministic seeded data.\n2. Add the restaurant catalog slice with `GET /api/restaurants` returning restaurant summaries and table capacity metadata, plus an integration test through the API entry point.\n3. Add the availability slice with a pure domain function to generate service slots and filter by date, party size, table capacity, and existing overlaps.\n4. Expose availability at `GET /api/restaurants/{restaurantId}/availability?date=YYYY-MM-DD&partySize=N` with boundary tests for invalid party size, invalid date, unknown restaurant, fully booked slots, and valid slots.\n5. Add the booking slice with a pure domain function to validate booking requests and select an available table without overlap.\n6. Expose bookings at `POST /api/bookings`, returning `201` confirmation on success and RFC ProblemDetails-style responses for expected failures.\n7. Test booking boundaries for invalid party size, invalid start time, unknown restaurant, overlapping reservations, adjacent non-overlapping reservations, and party too large.\n8. Add the existing bookings slice with `GET /api/bookings`, using optional restaurant/date filters only if quick, and test that created bookings appear in the list.\n9. Complete the OpenAPI quality pass with stable route names, tags, request/response DTOs, cheap examples, and unique operation IDs so Orval generates readable hooks/types.\n10. Export the generated OpenAPI document to `frontend/openapi/restaurant-booking.json` after backend endpoints stabilize.\n\n## Frontend Vertical Slices\n\n1. Bootstrap the React SPA with Vite, TypeScript, Tailwind CSS, shadcn/ui, TanStack Query, Orval, ESLint, Prettier, and dead-code tooling.\n2. Configure deterministic scripts: `build`, `typecheck`, `lint`, `format:check`, `deadcode`, and `generate:api`.\n3. Configure Orval against `frontend/openapi/restaurant-booking.json` with `client: react-query` and `httpClient: fetch`.\n4. Generate typed TanStack Query hooks and request/response types into `frontend/src/api/generated/` and use only that generated client for backend calls.\n5. Build a polished responsive app shell and restaurant list using shadcn `Card`, `Badge`, `Button`, `Skeleton`, `Alert`, and semantic Tailwind tokens.\n6. Build an accessible booking form with shadcn form components, date input, party size input, available slot selection, and generated availability query hooks keyed by restaurant/date/party size.\n7. Add booking mutation behavior with the generated hook, success confirmation panel/toast, and targeted invalidation for bookings and availability queries.\n8. Show expected API errors from ProblemDetails as clear inline form feedback.\n9. Add an existing bookings view using the generated bookings query hook, displayed as a responsive card/table hybrid with confirmation number, restaurant, date/time, party size, and status.\n\n## Verification Plan\n\n- Backend verification: run `dotnet build` with warnings as errors, `dotnet test --no-build`, and `dotnet format --verify-no-changes`.\n- Frontend verification: run dependency install, `npm run generate:api`, `npm run typecheck`, `npm run lint`, `npm run format:check`, `npm run deadcode`, and `npm run build`.\n- README verification: include backend/frontend setup, OpenAPI regeneration steps, all verification commands, and a note that in-memory data resets on restart.\n\n## Deliberate Constraints\n\n- Prefer in-memory storage over durable persistence to prioritize conflict behavior and typed client generation.\n- Avoid broad abstractions such as CQRS/MediatR or database repositories unless duplication appears.\n- Keep UI better than a plain form/list by using a two-column desktop layout, mobile-first stacking, clear confirmation states, loading skeletons, and accessible error messaging.\n- If implementation diverges from this plan, document the reason in the README or final notes.\n",
